   <text>
      <body>
         <cell style="font-size: 11pt;">Financial matter seems to be dealt with, expresses his gratitude. Says he has requested a letter from Erpenius, who is in Paris but will write upon his return. For any further help Tengnagel only needs to ask. Says the Arminians have been quiet since the 'plakkaat' that has gone out against them. Only preaching in Schoonhoven (I'm assuming this is the condemnation of Arminianism - amongst others - with the Synod of Dordt of 1618-19), which led to the arrest of the preacher and a riot in which one or two Arminians were shot by soldiers. Tried to preach in Alkmaar and Hoorn as well. Led to stationing of more soldiers in these cities, causing the Arminians to now be very quiet. Writes they no longer have a 'head' or leader now that Barnevelt (Van Oldenbarnevelt) is dead, and Grotius and Hogerbeets are imprisoned (they had been the safeguards of freedom of worship by making this a provincial issue, rather than a matter of the public church or the States General), and they don't have anyone of their confession in the cities or States. Mentions a writing of which the sale and reading is prohibited at a fine of 600 fl. Refers to the war, and to 'us Catholics' --&gt; suggests Van Wyninghen is catholic. Writes that the Catholics in Bohemia are fighting well, and that he hopes that the Duke of Brabant will be able to negotiate something good for them so that they can trade in ?? again. Seems to write his sickness prevents him from writing Aernoult. Wishes Tengnagel and his wife well. Sends his best to Pater Becamus (?) and Marcelius.</cell>
      </body>
